 are spared unnecessary toxicity and that resource allocation reflects risk stratification [Data: Entities (13); Relationships (30)].\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"There is robust protocol coverage for HR-negative/HER2-negative (triple negative) breast cancer.\",\n      \"explanation\": \"BINV-10 addresses the highly aggressive and challenging triple negative breast cancer (TNBC) subtype (HR-Negative/HER2-Negative), outlining dedicated systemic adjuvant recommendations. The protocol's linkage to common histologic types underscores its general applicability, ensuring that this high-need population receives standardized and effective therapy despite the lack of targetable receptors, which often limits treatment options [Data: Entities (0); Relationships (0)].\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"Stratification by menopausal status informs therapy for HR-positive/HER2-negative breast cancer.\",\n      \"explanation\": \"The protocols specifically differentiate between postmenopausal (BINV-6) and premenopausal (BINV-8) patients in the HR-Positive/HER2-Negative group, reflecting critical differences in response to endocrine therapies and risk profiles. This nuanced segmentation drives appropriate therapeutic intensity and duration, as well as surveillance recommendations, highlighting the guidelines' clinical sophistication in tailoring care to unique biologic contexts [Data: Entities (137, 151); Relationships (321, 378)].\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"Comprehensive surveillance and follow-up protocols are present for post-therapy breast cancer management.\",\n      \"explanation\": \"BINV-17 provides explicit steps for post-treatment surveillance and follow-up, recommending periodic exams and screenings to ensure early detection of recurrence and management of therapy-related complications. This protocol anchors survivorship care within the NCCN guidelines, reinforcing the importance of continuous patient engagement even after completion of active tr